what the process has been, our timeline, and then I'm gonna hand it over to Tim to talk about the RFP, the goals, our evaluation criteria, and discussion with you all.

45
00:03:58,946 --> 00:04:05,972
So just so that everybody is aware, I know the counselors know this, but we did have, in 2010, we signed a contract with Waste Management

46
00:04:07,075 --> 00:04:11,958
In 2021 we selected garbage to garden as a recommended curbside composting.

47
00:04:13,379 --> 00:04:26,067
We did this year extend the contract with waste management one year, because we have been advised that if any contractor is selected and even if it was to be waste management and they were to change their services in any manner.

48
00:04:26,615 --> 00:04:33,322
They would need a year to ramp up in order to have proper staffing to acquire new vehicles, et cetera.

49
00:04:33,662 --> 00:04:41,730
We've been advised that even waste management told us that they would want a year between the old contract before, between the signing of the contract

50
00:04:42,275 --> 00:04:47,479
and starting a new contract with us, in addition to any other vendor wanting that time.

51
00:04:48,640 --> 00:04:51,282
This year we also selected a preferred mattress hauler.

52
00:04:51,702 --> 00:04:57,807
Mattresses are no longer legally allowed to be disposed of in trash, which is what had been occurring in Medford.

53
00:04:58,687 --> 00:05:01,429
And we brought on HelpSee as a textile collection hauler.

54
00:05:03,031 --> 00:05:07,995
You know most of this, but this is what our current waste services are.

55
00:05:08,996 --> 00:05:13,880
A gallon, sorry, we do a trash toter, a recycling toter every other week.

56
00:05:14,541 --> 00:05:16,562
Yard waste is 15 weeks a year.

57
00:05:16,983 --> 00:05:22,787
Best practice according to DEP is to do at least 20 weeks a year of yard waste.

58
00:05:23,968 --> 00:05:25,970
You can get your white goods picked up for $26 for a curbside fee.

59
00:05:28,612 --> 00:05:34,317
We allow three bulk items per household to be picked up every other week.

60
00:05:34,738 --> 00:05:40,743
And I have to let you know that that costs the city $25 for every item, whether or not the item is picked up.

61
00:05:41,163 --> 00:05:50,631
There's about a 10 to 15% rate of scheduled pickups that the person doesn't put the item out and the city pays that $25 item.

62
00:05:50,991 --> 00:05:53,773
Anyhow, we're currently paying $400,000 a year for those items.

63
00:05:57,198 --> 00:06:01,303
Um, and there's a recycling overflow compactor at the city yard.

64
00:06:02,750 --> 00:06:06,191
Currently, everybody knows that we pick up single family homes.

65
00:06:06,732 --> 00:06:11,093
We're picking up all one to three family homes, municipal buildings, obviously.

66
00:06:11,533 --> 00:06:14,475
We're also picking up all the schools, including the Catholic schools.

67
00:06:14,975 --> 00:06:17,996
Most houses of worship in Medford get some level of service.

68
00:06:19,036 --> 00:06:25,679
The five business districts all get trash and recycling, although not all businesses are aware that they have recycling available to them.

69
00:06:26,939 --> 00:06:31,621
There are scattered businesses throughout the entire city that are on the city's waste pickup.

70
00:06:32,614 --> 00:06:40,540
There are at least 25 condominium buildings, and there are four housing authority sites that are currently being picked up by the city's contract.

71
00:06:42,981 --> 00:06:45,023
This is how much by pound.

72
00:06:46,224 --> 00:06:47,484
It's kind of interesting.

73
00:06:47,885 --> 00:06:48,545
This goes back to 2007.

74
00:06:48,605 --> 00:06:52,008
And you can see between 2007 and 2011, there was a reduction.

75
00:06:52,028 --> 00:06:53,689
2011 is when we moved to single stream recycling.

76
00:07:01,814 --> 00:07:15,282
and our waste amount from then plateaued for quite a while, our recycling completely plateaued, and that's when it went up to then and then it plateaued, and then there's the yard waste is that tiny little thing.

77
00:07:17,144 --> 00:07:26,710
Interestingly, during the pandemic, waste poundage went up noticeably, you can see that bump there, but not recycling or yard waste.

78
00:07:28,250 --> 00:07:30,252
So far with the RFP process,

79
00:07:31,376 --> 00:07:34,358
We did a community-wide survey in four languages.

80
00:07:34,918 --> 00:07:37,240
We had over 750 responses.

81
00:07:38,320 --> 00:07:42,723
We tabled at more than 10 community events and in public spaces.

82
00:07:43,364 --> 00:07:44,765
We hosted public meetings.

83
00:07:45,285 --> 00:07:48,187
We've been participating in the New England Regional Working Group.

84
00:07:48,607 --> 00:07:59,294
So this is a working group of communities in New England that are looking to get a new waste contract in the next year or two so that we meet regularly and compare notes.

85
00:08:00,805 --> 00:08:12,798
And then the consultants have spoken with 10 regional haulers, I mean, including waste management, but 10 of them, and all the major players have expressed interest in proposing for our contract.

86
00:08:13,899 --> 00:08:17,703
And then we've been strategizing on RFP approaches and options.

87
00:08:20,446 --> 00:08:20,927
Oh, sorry.

88
00:08:21,875 --> 00:08:25,760
So I realized that people were probably going to want to know what we learned from that survey.

89
00:08:26,681 --> 00:08:32,428
The biggest thing that people really pushed was that they wanted more education and clarity on waste.

90
00:08:32,568 --> 00:08:34,511
That was really the biggest thing we heard from them.

91
00:08:35,192 --> 00:08:40,599
People wanted more recycling, they wanted more yard waste pickup, they wanted more composting organics pickup.

92
00:08:41,410 --> 00:08:45,071
And they wanted more options for how to dispose of different types of waste.

93
00:08:45,591 --> 00:08:47,092
And there was concern about rodents.

94
00:08:47,632 --> 00:08:57,696
I'll just touch on rodents to say that our health department is very supportive of composting because it's commercial composting in these containers that have locked lids.

95
00:08:58,196 --> 00:09:03,658
And our garbage cans and our dumpsters do not have locked lids, but the compost bins do.

96
00:09:04,038 --> 00:09:05,819
So they're actually very supportive of this.

97
00:09:06,739 --> 00:09:09,840
In response to this desire for increased recycling,

98
00:09:10,715 --> 00:09:16,678
The DPW has actually been working on putting together a hazardous waste disposal day.

99
00:09:16,698 --> 00:09:18,739
I don't know if you want to get this in while I keep talking.

100
00:09:19,339 --> 00:09:24,201
So it's this Saturday, it's Saturday, April 8th, and there's a flyer for that.

101
00:09:24,221 --> 00:09:31,465
This flyer is going in all the water bills of the city in the first week of April.

102
00:09:33,275 --> 00:09:47,843
The graph sort of indicates how, sorry, it's not, it's really hard to read, but it's about what different kinds of things people want to dispose of, how satisfied they are with the current process and what different processes they want.

103
00:09:49,083 --> 00:09:52,025
It's not really, we could go into it if there's interest.

104
00:09:55,736 --> 00:10:01,381
So this is actually, I should ask Tim to hand those out, because looking ahead, what's next?

105
00:10:01,862 --> 00:10:03,624
And this is our process moving forward.

106
00:10:03,644 --> 00:10:07,667
Tim, do you want to just use my computer to show the graphs there?

107
00:10:07,928 --> 00:10:08,308
Sure.

108
00:10:08,428 --> 00:10:09,970
Okay.

109
00:10:10,310 --> 00:10:13,093
All right.

110
00:10:13,113 --> 00:10:15,335
My name is Tim McGibbon, Commissioner of Public Works.

111
00:10:15,875 --> 00:10:16,376
Thank you for

112
00:10:17,302 --> 00:10:19,144
hearing us and having this discussion tonight.

113
00:10:19,924 --> 00:10:21,285
So what's next?

114
00:10:22,206 --> 00:10:24,148
So this is a timeline that we have in front of us.

115
00:10:24,688 --> 00:10:33,395
So the key step here is reviewing the RFP and having pre-proposal meetings with haulers.

116
00:10:33,776 --> 00:10:35,958
That's really what's happening right now.

117
00:10:36,598 --> 00:10:37,519
That's taking us into March.

118
00:10:39,141 --> 00:10:42,964
we're gonna receive proposals back in June 2023, and then awarding a contract in beginning of July 2023.

119
00:10:43,525 --> 00:10:46,687
And then 12 months later, July 1st, 2024, the new operations begin.

120
00:10:55,212 --> 00:11:24,589
Okay, so just, I'm not gonna read all these goals, you can get into the details, but out of all that work that Alicia just talked about, we came out at this point in the process with some goals, controlling the cost, fairness, transparency, expanding the recycling and composting programs and service, taking a step towards zero waste, and also decreasing multiple haulers in our business districts, and if we can capture that in the process as well.

121
00:11:28,600 --> 00:11:37,469
So procurement notes, just so everybody understands, is a process that we're following, but it doesn't fall under typical public procurement law.

122
00:11:37,589 --> 00:11:39,211
So we're exempt from a lot of the laws.

123
00:11:39,271 --> 00:11:43,816
However, it's very important to understand that we want a very competitive process.

124
00:11:44,396 --> 00:12:05,615
We are doing an RFP process, so we're going to be reviewing proposals that different haulers give us, and then we're going to evaluate those proposals and look at the prices that they're offering associated with those services and choose based off of specific evaluation criteria that is defined in the RFP.

125
00:12:09,493 --> 00:12:16,761
So this allows, obviously a competitive marketplace, it allows us to compare prices for services proposed by different companies.

126
00:12:17,702 --> 00:12:25,931
And it also allows us to negotiate that service and price when we enter a contract with whoever wins that contest effectively.

127
00:12:25,951 --> 00:12:30,937
And one of the ways we'd like to partner with city council is we'd like to enter a contract that's longer than three years

128
00:12:31,570 --> 00:12:33,510
with options for extensions as well.

129
00:12:33,951 --> 00:12:41,472
So moving forward, especially when we get into the contract stage, but likely before that, obviously, coordinating that with you all.

130
00:12:43,833 --> 00:12:51,234
So the way that the RFP is structured is, you know, as you can imagine, there's a lot of services kind of within the realm of solid waste services.

131
00:12:51,334 --> 00:12:58,016
So we have broken this down, obviously with our consultant, to a few different scopes that bidders can bid on.

132
00:12:58,236 --> 00:12:59,276
They can bid on all three,

133
00:12:59,996 --> 00:13:06,420
I'm sorry, the language I'm using, it's not a bid, they can respond with a proposal to all three or just one.

134
00:13:07,360 --> 00:13:19,407
So as you can see, scope A is the major scope, that's our trash, that's our yard trimmings, that's our recyclables, white goods, so the bulk of the products that we dispose of.

135
00:13:19,907 --> 00:13:24,210
Scope B is organics, so that's your curbside compost pickup.

136
00:13:24,710 --> 00:13:26,571
And then scope C, bulky items.

137
00:13:29,312 --> 00:13:38,237
part of what we're trying to do here, because we have these three different scopes and we know that we're setting this up so we can evaluate it.

138
00:13:38,537 --> 00:13:45,421
Based off of those scopes, we'd like to participate in a preferred hauler program with this new contract.

139
00:13:45,541 --> 00:13:49,323
So basically the winner of scope A also becomes preferred hauler.

140
00:13:49,803 --> 00:13:57,107
In order to do that, we would need to continue our partnership with city council to have a ordinance in place that would

141
00:13:57,507 --> 00:14:02,830
that we're going to be able to tie together recyclables and trash disposal from our haulers that enter the city and do service here.

142
00:14:03,270 --> 00:14:06,372
So Councilor Collins, I know, has been working on that.

143
00:14:06,612 --> 00:14:07,713
We've been in communication.

144
00:14:08,853 --> 00:14:15,857
The team that's working on this at City Hall as well as the City Council subcommittee that's working on this.

145
00:14:16,037 --> 00:14:19,359
So we'll continue to march down that road.

146
00:14:19,759 --> 00:14:23,461
Basically, this is a way to create efficiency, minimize the number of trucks.

147
00:14:23,881 --> 00:14:26,423
So in other words, the preferred hauler that is

148
00:14:28,993 --> 00:14:55,781
solicited from a large office building or something like that, they can work their route for those private services with the city route, create efficiencies, and we charge a user fee that captures the fuel costs and the disposal costs of that waste that then gets put into an enterprise account that feeds back into the system to help us pay the processing fees.

149
00:14:56,461 --> 00:15:04,429
So we have a lot of detail on that and we can certainly answer questions tonight, but we're going to have more time to answer those questions and get to the bottom of it.

150
00:15:07,190 --> 00:15:09,911
Scope A, so who are we talking about, who are we servicing?

151
00:15:10,511 --> 00:15:18,875
The goal here really is to not really, we're mimicking what we do now and we're trying to improve it, so that's really the key here.

152
00:15:19,135 --> 00:15:24,417
But we'll also try to add transparency and some sort of clarity on how the process works.

153
00:15:25,377 --> 00:15:31,300
So residential dwelling units that are between one and four units, commercial buildings that are relatively small, up to 25,

154
00:15:32,560 --> 00:15:33,141
100 square feet.

155
00:15:33,941 --> 00:15:49,528
Business districts have services now that we're trying to mimic moving forward, houses of worship K 12 schools, so as you can see the list is very similar to the list that Alicia presented on what we're doing now, probably the biggest difference is those condominium buildings are no longer included.

156
00:15:50,028 --> 00:15:52,629
So that's one of the bigger takeaways here.

157
00:15:53,429 --> 00:16:00,431
And that's really to level the playing field and to get us on track with what is best practices out there.

158
00:16:01,372 --> 00:16:06,993
And one of the ideas that I think a lot of people have in their mind is these rows of carts that are serviced and picked up.

159
00:16:07,914 --> 00:16:08,674
That's not ideal.

160
00:16:08,834 --> 00:16:14,796
So we would like to move to more of a container system and a preferred hauler with a lower rate that is negotiated.

161
00:16:15,476 --> 00:16:17,717
So that's really the direction we're trying to hit.

162
00:16:20,357 --> 00:16:32,149
So the scope of services, the change here that we're exploring is moving from every week trash pickup to bi-weekly trash pickup, but that goes right alongside compost pickup.

163
00:16:32,670 --> 00:16:35,512
Compost is the dirty, smelly, wet, heavy stuff.

164
00:16:36,253 --> 00:16:42,780
Trash is the drier, not as smelly, not that big of a deal to have sitting around a little bit longer.

165
00:16:43,260 --> 00:16:44,861
in your garage type situation.

166
00:16:44,961 --> 00:16:56,869
So we're looking at changing trash every other week with the 64 gallon container, and then keeping the recycling the way it is, that really wouldn't change much for the average user.

167
00:16:57,649 --> 00:16:57,929
And then

168
00:16:59,580 --> 00:17:03,825
that every other week trash and weekly compost, like I said, go together.

169
00:17:03,945 --> 00:17:09,530
So what today is compost and trash is separated in the future.

170
00:17:09,911 --> 00:17:23,043
So you're taking, you know, 25 to 30% of your, whatever the number is, 50% of your trash, putting it into the compost bin with a lockable, a sealable lid and putting your trash into another bin that is getting collected every other week.

171
00:17:23,724 --> 00:17:27,867
Knowing that that is relatively new, cutting edge, it's the direction we'd like to head in.

172
00:17:28,147 --> 00:17:36,132
We're also getting prices in this process so we can understand what weekly trash pickup looks like as well.

173
00:17:36,392 --> 00:17:39,955
But I will say we're looking at balancing costs and controlling costs here too.

174
00:17:40,395 --> 00:17:46,739
So obviously we are looking at what happens when we increase costs for compost pickup.

175
00:17:47,059 --> 00:17:50,802
We have to find some place to decrease costs to stay within a reasonable budget.

176
00:17:51,122 --> 00:17:57,192
So that's the game that we're playing and we'll have a lot more pieces to play that game with once we get responses back from the RFP.

177
00:17:59,694 --> 00:18:00,575
evaluation criteria.

178
00:18:00,615 --> 00:18:02,536
This is where City Council could certainly help us.

179
00:18:03,096 --> 00:18:08,359
This is something that will be some work, and it's evaluating what comes back in this proposal.

180
00:18:08,440 --> 00:18:13,263
It's obviously, if not the city's biggest contract, one of the city's biggest contracts.

181
00:18:13,643 --> 00:18:21,247
So what we'd like to evaluate it based on is experience of the haulers, references those haulers have, key personnel qualifications.

182
00:18:21,648 --> 00:18:26,771
We anticipate working directly with somebody as a liaison from one of these companies directly with the city.

183
00:18:27,492 --> 00:18:35,941
Transition and implementation plan, which is going to be critical in my mind because I'd like to iron out every possible wrinkle of operation before we implement.

184
00:18:36,602 --> 00:18:43,009
Plan of services, what exactly are they doing, how are they doing it, and what can the resident and other expect.

185
00:18:43,570 --> 00:18:45,452
Financial responsibility of the company.

186
00:18:46,233 --> 00:18:49,114
customer service, outreach and education.

187
00:18:49,394 --> 00:18:50,195
That's a huge piece.

188
00:18:50,615 --> 00:19:05,362
As Alicia mentioned, that is going to be something that we're going to be exploring, getting some help on understanding exactly what the city is going to need to do from an outreach and education standpoint, environmental benefits, value added offerings and anything else.

189
00:19:06,122 --> 00:19:07,283
I also say the outreach and education.

190
00:19:07,323 --> 00:19:13,587
We're also asking, as you noticed in the RFP, we're asking the respondents to help us out considerably in that arena as well.

191
00:19:13,667 --> 00:19:15,508
So that would be part of the expectation.

192
00:19:15,548 --> 00:19:20,651
They're just not going to let us hang while we try to transition to potentially a new set of operations.

193
00:19:24,293 --> 00:19:25,394
All right, well, thank you very much.

194
00:19:25,574 --> 00:19:28,435
And the rest of the time is we could take the discussion where you'd like to take it.

195
00:19:28,475 --> 00:19:32,798
We have our consultants on board, and we're happy to answer questions and take it wherever you'd like.

196
00:19:35,175 --> 00:19:44,340
So if you could, just on the timeline that's up on the screen, is that ideal or are we going to have to get there by, you know, is that June, July, 2023?

197
00:19:44,700 --> 00:19:48,082
And sorry, maybe the transcript is covering what I can see here.

